    <item>
      <title>Global dynamics in systems biology</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/event/siam-ds25/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 May 2025 13:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/event/siam-ds25/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;This talk presents recent advances in understanding global dynamics in systems biology using combinatorial and topological methods. The presentation focuses on applications of Conley Index Theory to gene regulatory networks and demonstrates how these mathematical frameworks can provide rigorous insights into complex biological systems.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Computational dynamics of gene regulatory networks</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/event/dynamics-seminar/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 01 Apr 2025 13:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/event/dynamics-seminar/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;This seminar presents computational approaches to studying the dynamics of gene regulatory networks. The talk explores how mathematical models and computational tools can be used to analyze and predict the behavior of complex biological systems, with a focus on rigorous methods for identifying global dynamics.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Network dynamics via combinatorics, topology and homology</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/event/ams-seminar/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 01 Mar 2025 13:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/event/ams-seminar/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;This seminar explores the intersection of combinatorics, topology, and homology in the study of network dynamics. The presentation demonstrates how these mathematical frameworks can be combined to analyze complex networks, with applications to biological systems and gene regulatory networks. The talk highlights recent advances in using algebraic topological methods to understand the global behavior of dynamical systems.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
    </item>
    
